[SourceTitle "01 Exchange Variation, 5...Qd6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/56931"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Thus starts the Ruy Lopez, or Spanish game. If you 
don't know the first couple moves already, make sure to select'Learn All Moves' 
and not just the key moves. This course will assume you know the beginning of 
the Ruy Lopez, and start on blacks reply to 3.Bb5 if you select'Learn Key Moves 
Only' and could save you some time if you don't want to go through the whole 
thing each time you learn a new variation.} a6 {This is the main line, and most 
common 3rd move from black (at least at the club level). Black asks white what 
he intends to do with his bishop. 4.Ba4 is most popular, and tends to have good 
results for white, but I think 4.Bxc6 is just a bit easier for white to play. 
Yes, you give up the bishop pair, but you create double pawns for black which 
stay a weakness for a long time.} 4. Bxc6 {And here we have the Ruy Lopez: 
Exchange Variation, which will be our respones to 3...a6.nnIn the Exchange 
Variation, we give up the bishop pair, but there isn't as much theory to learn, 
and white's plan is farily easy to grasp: Trade pieces and go for the endgame. 
After dxc6, white's pawn structure is superior for an ending, so, go for it. 
It's practical.} dxc6 {Black nearly always recaptures with the d pawn to open 
the file for the Queen, though sometimes takes with the b pawn and ends up 
putting the a8 rook on the half open b file.} 5. O-O {It almost looks like white 
could just take the e5 pawn, but after 5...Qd4, white must lose either the 
Knight or the pawn on e4. O-O is the most popular choice for white here; it is 
solid and we're going with it.} Qd6 {Not the best way to defend the pawn for 
black, but playable. The pawn does need to be defended however. Before O-O, 
white could not take the pawn because Qd4 or Qd5 forking the knight and pawn, 
and after the knight moves the queen takes the pawn. But after 5.O-O, if the 
queen takes the pawn, white has Rf1, skewering the queen and king.} 6. b3 Ne7 7. 
d3 {White uses his pawns to gain more control of the light squares now that his 
light-squared bishop is gone. This also ensures maximum mobility for the 
remaining bishop.} f6 8. Nbd2 {looking to force the queen to move again...} Be6 
9. Nc4 Qd7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Qe2 {Connecting the rooks and completing 
development.} Ng6 {Black is eyeing the f4 square for his knight.} 12. Rfd1 *

