1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 {In the Schliemann, black is giving up a bit of 
King safety and trying to weaken white's presence in the center.} 4. Qe2 {4.Nc3 
is also worth looking into, though we're focusing on Qe2.} Nf6 {Adding more 
pressure to e4.} 5. exf5 {Just take it.} Be7 {Black clears the path to castle.} 
6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bxc6 dxc6 {Like in the 3...a6 lines, we're going to give up the 
bishop pair here (even though not prompted with a7-a5 first) give white double 
pawns on the C file AND an isolated e pawn which we will hopefully trade for our 
own doubled f pawn.} 8. Qc4+ Kh8 9. Nxe5 Bxf5 10. O-O Bxc2 11. d4 b5 12. Qe2 b4 
13. Qxc2 bxc3 14. bxc3 *

