[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/57384"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {The Steinitz Defense. Solid but passive, so you 
probably won't see it often.} 4. d4 exd4 5. Qxd4 Nge7 6. Qc3 a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bb3 
{Black would eventually like to trap white's bishop by playing c5 then c4.} h6 
{Black dissuades white from putting a knight or bishop on g5.} 9. O-O b4 10. Qe3 
a5 11. a3 {White wouldn't mind having the a-file open for his rook.} Bd7 12. Qf4 
{Creating an instant checkmate threat on f7. After white deals with it (or loses 
immediately!) you should have a comfortable enough game.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Steinitz Defense"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Steinitz Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Steinitz Defense"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/57385"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 exd4 5. Qxd4 Nge7 {Now black can keep their 
pawn structure intact if white captures on c6.} 6. Qc3 a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bb3 h6 9. 
O-O Be6 10. Bd5 Qd7 11. Re1 *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Steinitz Defense"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Steinitz Defense"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "05 Steinitz Defense"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/57386"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 exd4 5. Qxd4 Bd7 {If black wants to unpin 
the knight, take it and don't worry too much about losing the bishop pair.} 6. 
Bxc6 Bxc6 7. O-O Nf6 {Black attacks whites e-pawn a second time.} 8. Re1 
{Defends the pawn and puts the rook on the same file as Black's king.} Be7 
{Black clears a path to castle.} 9. Nc3 Qd7 {Black delays castling and opens the 
option to castle queenside as well.} 10. b3 {Preparing to fianchetto the bishop 
and simultaneously connect the rooks, completing development} O-O 11. Bb2 Rfe8 
{Black puts the rook on the half open file.} 12. Rad1 {Bringing the rook to its 
optimal location.} *

