[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58166"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 {A common way to defend the 
pawn, which does need defending now that white has castled.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 
c5 8. Ne2 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 {Now we'll get a queenless middle-game, and again work 
toward exchanging off pieces to get the superior ending.} Bd7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. 
Nbc3 Re8 12. Rd2 Bc6 13. Rad1 b6 {Note that black can't take the pawn until 
giving some air to his king, due to the back-rank checkmate after Bxe4?, Nxe4, 
Rxe4??, Rd8#.} 14. a4 {And now we attack black's castled position.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58167"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. c3 Ne7 {Again 
we will put the question to the bishop.} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Ng6 10. Be3 Bd6 11. 
a3 Qe7 12. Nd2 O-O-O 13. Qe2 {White's goal remains the same. Try to keep the 
superior pawn structure and trade down to an ending. Try to keep this in mind 
when playing the exchange variation.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58168"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. c3 exd4 {I 
don't like this line for black, mostly because it leaves white with a nice 
center and leaves black with uncoordinated pieces and a bishop with too many 
friendly pawns on the same color.} 8. cxd4 c5 9. d5 Bd6 10. Be3 Ne7 {Clearingn 
the path to castle...} 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. Rc1 b6 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58189"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. c3 Qe7 8. h3 
Bh5 {This line seems much better for black than trading the bishop for the 
knight. At the end of this line both sides are just about equal, though Houdini 
maintains white has a very slight advantage.} 9. b3 O-O-O 10. Ba3 Qe6 11. Bxf8 
Rxf8 {With both knights on the board here, it would make sense for white to 
continue by not opening up the center too soon, and as always in the Exchange 
Variation, try to maintain the superior pawn structure and trade down.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58191"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 
{Black wants to avoid trading queens for the moment, so he blocks the d-file. 
Should white move his knight, no discovery on the queen exists.} 8. Be3 Ne7 9. 
Nd2 {Looking to bring the knight up to d4 next.} O-O 10. Nc4 Ng6 11. c3 b5 12. 
Nxd6 {This looks like it gives black the chance to undouble his pawns, but if he 
does, then Nxc6 wins a pawn.} Qxd6 13. Qb3+ {Next we'll put a rook on d1 and 
continue with the standard Exchange Variation plan.} Kh8 14. Rfd1 *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58192"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. 
Ne2 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Be6 10. Bf4 Bd6 11. Bxd6 O-O-O 12. Nf4 {White can't simply take 
the pawn due to the bank rank mate, Rxd1#. Instead, we force black to move his 
bishop (thereby improving the position of our knight) before allowing him to 
capture our bishop.} Bf7 13. Nc3 {Finishing development and removing the bank 
rank threat.} cxd6 {Now black must take the bishop or else we'll take the pawn. 
If black takes with the rook, we play 14.Rxd6 cxd6 15.Nfd5.} 14. Nfd5 Bxd5 15. 
Nxd5 {An excellent outpost for the knight. Black is having trouble getting his 
Knight into the game. If he plays Nh6, we play f3.} *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
