[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58193"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. 
Ne2 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Nbc3 Bd6 {This is probably a better way 
for black to play than 11...Re8, ending slightly better development, but still 
white maintains the better pawn-structure and will look to enter a winning 
endgame.} 12. Bf4 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 Ne7 14. f3 *

[Event "Ruy Lopez common lines"]
[Site "Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "06 Exchange Variation, 5...f6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58194"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. 
Ne2 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. Be3 O-O-O 11. Nbc3 Re8 12. Rd2 Bc6 13. Rad1 Bxe4 {Black 
must not take this pawn!} 14. Nxe4 {Now black is just down a piece for for one 
pawn, and white will have an easy game.} Rxe4 {Unless black blunders the game 
entirely!} 15. Rd8# {Black assumed the d4 square was sufficiently guarded to 
take white's pawn, but he forgot about his back rank weakness.} *

