1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bc5 {Not my favorite move by 
black. It's playable, but there's a lot of maneuvring around and it just isn't 
as fun (for players like me anyway).} 6. Nxe5 {Grab the pawn since black left it 
open.} Be6 7. d3 {Opening the way for the bishop later.} Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 
{The Bishop is just fine on c1 right now. Better to keep a pesky black piece 
from entering g4.} Nd7 10. Nf3 f6 {f6 prepares a spot for blacks knight on e5.} 
11. Bf4 {Adding more control to the e5 square and tying down Black's queen to 
defense of the currently immobile c7 pawn.} Bf7 12. Qd2 {Connecting the rooks 
and completing development. Also there is no longer a pin threat against the 
knight.} Re8 13. Be3 {Offering the trade, it's only good for us if black 
accepts.} Bd6 14. Nd4 {Whites pieces are placed well. From here we'll probably 
bring our knight over to f6 (threatening the bishop on d6, which we will take if 
black lets us), grab space with a4 and b3, and move our bishop to f4.} *

