[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58582"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 {If white captures the knight on c6, black can 
retake with its brother, preserving a nice pawn structure on the queen-side, as 
well as preserving the defense of the pawn on e5.} 4. Nc3 {Getting the second 
knight out before castling.} d6 5. O-O Bd7 {Black breaks the pin on the knight.} 
6. h3 {Discouraging the black bishop from moving to g4.} Ng6 {Black eyes the f4 
square for their knight, which would put pressure on h3. White wouldn't be able 
to play g3 to kick the knight because of Nxh3+.} 7. Nd5 {Now white can simply 
trade knights of black tries to invade. This move also ties down Black's queen 
to the defense of c7 (if her majesty leaves, Nxc7+ is very strong indeed).} Nd4 
8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. b3 c6 {Black drives back the annoying knight on d5} 10. Ne3 Be7 
11. Nxd4 {Simplifying a bit and doubling Black's pawns at the same time.} exd4 
12. Nf5 Bf6 13. Bb2 c5 14. c3 Ne7 {Attacking the knight a second time, forcing 
white to move or defend.} 15. Qg4 {White threatens Nxg7+.} Nxf5 16. exf5 O-O 17. 
cxd4 Rfe8 18. Rac1 *

