[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/58595"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 {If white captures the knight on c6, black can 
retake with its brother, preserving a nice pawn structure on the queen-side, as 
well as preserving the defense of the pawn on e5.} 4. Nc3 a6 {This time Black 
puts the question to whites bishop.} 5. Bc4 Ng6 6. O-O d6 {Black opens the 
diagonal to get his bishop in the game. This is important for black, because so 
far they have only the two knights developed, while white has both knights and a 
bishop developed AND has already castled while black is still at least two moves 
away from castling. Black must develop.} 7. Nd5 {As in the previous line, Nd5 
encourages Blacks queen to stay put for the time being.} Bg4 {Black pins the 
knight.} 8. c3 {This game is looking very Italian-ish.} Nh4 {Black threatens to 
take on f3 and ruin the king's pawn cover, as white cannot take back with the 
queen.} 9. Be2 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {Black trades off the pieces and 
play continues.} Be7 {Getting ready to castle.} 12. Qg3 O-O 13. d3 {White opens 
up the bishop.} Bh4 {A better move here for black would be Ne7, getting ready to 
swing over to g6 and possibly f4.} 14. Qg4 {The black Queen looks over worked 
here, defending d7 and the bishop h4} Bf6 {Solving the overworked queen dilemma 
(not that it was such a big dilemma).} 15. f4 exf4 16. d4 {Keeping the black 
knight out of e5. And just look at the lovely center white has!} Bg5 17. Bxf4 
Bxf4 18. Rxf4 Ne7 19. Nf6+ {Taking advantage of the pin on the g7 pawn.} Kh8 20. 
Qh3 {Threatens Qxh7#} h6 21. Raf1 *

