[Comment "ruy-lopez-common-lines/course/1254, variation/59780"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. Nc3 a6 5. Bc4 b5 6. Bb3 {Keeping the bishop 
on the a2-g8 diagonal.} Ng6 {Black frees the diagonal for his bishop to join the 
game, as well as eyeing f4 for his knight.} 7. d3 {Opening the diagonal for 
whites bishop and defending the e4 pawn.} h6 {Black doesn't want white putting 
any pieces on g5.} 8. O-O {The king is safe and development is almost complete, 
where as black's development is lagging behind.} Bb7 9. a4 {This creates an 
escape for white's bishop on a2.} Na5 10. Ba2 c6 11. axb5 axb5 {The a-file is 
now open.} 12. Be3 {preparing to open the center.} Be7 {Black is ready to castle 
finally.} 13. d4 {Prying open the center. Black can take the pawn, in which case 
we retake with the knight, or Black can play b4 and we retreat the knight to 
e2.} d6 {Black wants to keep a pawn on e5.} 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Qxd8+ {Black can 
take with the rook, as he does in this line, but in so doing he also removes the 
only defender of the knight on a5.nnIf Black were foolish enough to take with 
the Queen, we play 16.Bxf7, and then if Kc7 we have Bxg6. Or if 16...Nc4 we play 
Rxa8+. Or if 16...Nh4 then Bb6+. And white is winning in all cases.nnTherefore, 
black recaptures with the rook and preserves the right to castle (but not for 
long!)} Rxd8 16. Bxf7+ {Since the knight is no longer defended on a5, we can 
take this pawn.} Kxf7 17. Rxa5 {And white is up a pawn with a much safer king.} 
*

